<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="268" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="4.[96,746,1232,1971]" pageId="4" pageNumber="268">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[96,235,1232,1256]" pageId="4" pageNumber="268">Distribution</emphasis>
– Endemic to south-eastern D.R. Congo (Haut Katanga).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="268" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[96,746,1232,1971]" pageId="4" pageNumber="268">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[96,183,1299,1323]" pageId="4" pageNumber="268">Habitat</emphasis>
– Shaded vertical siliceous rock faces, often on metalliferous rocks, e.g. malachite, or rarely on nonmineralized rocks, 1200–1500 m elevation. Malachite is a copper carbonate hydroxide mineral [Cu 
<subScript attach="both" box="[529,537,1405,1419]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="268">2</subScript>
CO 
<subScript attach="left" box="[573,581,1405,1419]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="268">3</subScript>
(OH) 
<subScript attach="none" box="[637,645,1405,1419]" fontSize="6" pageId="4" pageNumber="268">2</subScript>
]. It often results from the weathering of copper ores.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="4" pageNumber="268" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="4.[96,746,1232,1971]" pageId="4" pageNumber="268">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[96,219,1456,1480]" pageId="4" pageNumber="268">Etymology</emphasis>
– Named after the metalliferous rocks which are the preferred habitat.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
